# Jira CLI

JiraCLI is a feature-rich interactive command line tool for Atlassian Jira that helps you avoid the Jira web UI. It provides comprehensive functionality for managing issues, epics, sprints, and boards directly from your terminal with both interactive and non-interactive modes.

The tool supports both Jira Cloud and on-premise (Server/Data Center) installations, offering multiple authentication methods including basic auth, bearer tokens (PAT), and mTLS. It features an interactive TUI (terminal user interface) with vim-like navigation, plain text output modes for scripting, and raw JSON output for automation workflows.

## Installation

### Install via Homebrew (macOS)

```bash
# Add the tap and install
brew tap ankitpokhrel/jira-cli
brew install jira-cli
```

### Install via Go

```bash
# Install using go install (requires Go 1.16+)
go install github.com/ankitpokhrel/jira-cli/cmd/jira@latest
```

### Install via Docker

```bash
# Run jira-cli in a Docker container
docker run -it --rm ghcr.io/ankitpokhrel/jira-cli:latest
```

### Install on Windows (Scoop)

```powershell
# Install via Scoop package manager
scoop bucket add extras
scoop install jira-cli
```

## Configuration

### Initialize Jira CLI Configuration

The `jira init` command sets up the configuration required for the tool to connect to your Jira instance. It creates a configuration file with server details, authentication, default project, and board settings.

```bash
# Interactive configuration setup
jira init

# Non-interactive setup for Jira Cloud
export JIRA_API_TOKEN="your-api-token"
jira init --installation cloud --server https://your-domain.atlassian.net --login your-email@example.com --project PRJ --board "Sprint Board"

# Non-interactive setup for on-premise with basic auth
export JIRA_API_TOKEN="your-password"
jira init --installation local --server https://jira.company.com --login username --project PRJ --board "Dev Board"

# Setup with bearer token authentication (PAT)
export JIRA_AUTH_TYPE=bearer
export JIRA_API_TOKEN="your-personal-access-token"
jira init --installation local --server https://jira.company.com --project PRJ

# Setup with insecure TLS (for self-signed certificates)
jira init --insecure

# Force overwrite existing configuration
jira init --force
```

## Issue Management

### List Issues

The `jira issue list` command searches and displays issues with extensive filtering options. Issues are shown in an interactive table by default with vim-like navigation.

```bash
# List recent issues in the configured project
jira issue list

# List issues with specific filters
jira issue list -s"In Progress" -yHigh -a$(jira me)

# List issues created in the last 7 days
jira issue list --created -7d

# List issues updated this week assigned to no one
jira issue list --updated week -ax

# List issues with specific type and resolution
jira issue list -tBug -R"Won't Do"

# List issues with multiple labels
jira issue list -lbackend -l"high-prio"

# List issues in plain text mode (for scripting)
jira issue list --plain --no-headers

# List specific columns only
jira issue list --plain --columns key,assignee,status

# Output as raw JSON
jira issue list --raw

# Output as CSV
jira issue list --csv

# Paginate results (get 50 items starting from item 10)
jira issue list --paginate 10:50

# Execute raw JQL query
jira issue list -q "summary ~ cli AND status != Done"

# Search for text in issues
jira issue list "Feature Request"

# List issues in a different project
jira issue list -pOTHER

# List issues you are watching
jira issue list -w

# List recently accessed issues
jira issue list --history
```

### Create Issue

The `jira issue create` command creates a new issue with support for interactive prompts, templates, and custom fields.

```bash
# Create issue interactively
jira issue create

# Create issue with all parameters (non-interactive)
jira issue create -tBug -s"Login button not working" -yHigh -lbug -lurgent -b"Users cannot click the login button on mobile devices" --no-input

# Create issue and attach to an epic
jira issue create -tStory -s"Implement dark mode" -PEPIC-42

# Create issue with custom fields
jira issue create -tStory -s"Issue with story points" --custom story-points=3

# Create issue in a different project
jira issue create -pOTHER -tTask -s"Cross-project task"

# Create issue with fix version
jira issue create -tBug -s"Critical bug" --fix-version v2.0

# Create issue with component
jira issue create -tTask -s"Backend task" -CBackend

# Create issue from template file
jira issue create -tStory -s"Feature implementation" --template /path/to/template.md

# Create issue from stdin
echo "Description from stdin" | jira issue create -s"New Task" -tTask --no-input

# Create issue and open in browser
jira issue create -tBug -s"UI Bug" --web

# Create issue with JSON output
jira issue create -tTask -s"Scripted task" --no-input --raw
# Output: {"id":"10001","key":"PRJ-123","self":"https://..."}
```

### View Issue

The `jira issue view` command displays detailed information about an issue including description, comments, and linked issues.

```bash
# View issue details
jira issue view ISSUE-1

# View issue with 5 recent comments
jira issue view ISSUE-1 --comments 5

# View issue in plain text mode
jira issue view ISSUE-1 --plain

# Get raw JSON response
jira issue view ISSUE-1 --raw
```

### Edit Issue

The `jira issue edit` command modifies existing issue fields including summary, description, priority, labels, and custom fields.

```bash
# Edit issue interactively
jira issue edit ISSUE-1

# Edit summary and priority non-interactively
jira issue edit ISSUE-1 -s"Updated summary" -yMedium --no-input

# Edit description
jira issue edit ISSUE-1 -b"New description content" --no-input

# Add labels (append to existing)
jira issue edit ISSUE-1 -lnew-label -lanother-label

# Remove a label (prefix with minus)
jira issue edit ISSUE-1 --label -old-label

# Add and remove labels in one command
jira issue edit ISSUE-1 --label -p2 --label p1

# Update components
jira issue edit ISSUE-1 -CBackend -C-Frontend

# Update fix versions
jira issue edit ISSUE-1 --fix-version v2.0 --fix-version -v1.0

# Update assignee
jira issue edit ISSUE-1 -a"john.doe@example.com"

# Unassign issue
jira issue edit ISSUE-1 -ax

# Edit from stdin
echo "Updated description" | jira issue edit ISSUE-1 --no-input

# Edit custom fields
jira issue edit ISSUE-1 --custom story-points=5

# Edit without notifying watchers
jira issue edit ISSUE-1 -s"Silent update" --skip-notify --no-input
```

### Assign Issue

The `jira issue assign` command assigns or unassigns users to/from issues.

```bash
# Assign interactively
jira issue assign

# Assign to specific user by email
jira issue assign ISSUE-1 john@example.com

# Assign to user by display name
jira issue assign ISSUE-1 "John Doe"

# Assign to yourself
jira issue assign ISSUE-1 $(jira me)

# Assign to default assignee
jira issue assign ISSUE-1 default

# Unassign issue
jira issue assign ISSUE-1 x
```

### Move/Transition Issue

The `jira issue move` command transitions an issue from one status to another based on available workflow transitions.

```bash
# Move issue interactively (shows available transitions)
jira issue move ISSUE-1

# Move to specific state
jira issue move ISSUE-1 "In Progress"
jira issue move ISSUE-1 Done

# Move with a comment
jira issue move ISSUE-1 "In Progress" --comment "Started working on this"

# Move with resolution and assignee
jira issue move ISSUE-1 Done -RFixed -a$(jira me)

# Move and open in browser
jira issue move ISSUE-1 Done --web
```

### Clone Issue

The `jira issue clone` command duplicates an issue with the ability to override metadata.

```bash
# Clone issue
jira issue clone ISSUE-1

# Clone with modified summary
jira issue clone ISSUE-1 -s"Cloned: Original summary"

# Clone with different priority and assignee
jira issue clone ISSUE-1 -yHigh -a$(jira me)

# Clone with text replacement in summary and description
jira issue clone ISSUE-1 -H"old-text:new-text"

# Clone with different labels
jira issue clone ISSUE-1 -lcloned -lneeds-review

# Clone and open in browser
jira issue clone ISSUE-1 --web
```

### Delete Issue

The `jira issue delete` command removes an issue from Jira.

```bash
# Delete issue interactively
jira issue delete

# Delete specific issue
jira issue delete ISSUE-1

# Delete issue with all subtasks
jira issue delete ISSUE-1 --cascade
```

### Link Issues

The `jira issue link` command creates relationships between two issues.

```bash
# Link issues interactively
jira issue link

# Link with specific relationship type
jira issue link ISSUE-1 ISSUE-2 Blocks
jira issue link ISSUE-1 ISSUE-2 Duplicate
jira issue link ISSUE-1 ISSUE-2 "is blocked by"

# Add remote web link to issue
jira issue link remote ISSUE-1 https://github.com/org/repo/pull/123 "Related PR"
```

### Unlink Issues

The `jira issue unlink` command removes links between issues.

```bash
# Unlink interactively
jira issue unlink

# Unlink specific issues
jira issue unlink ISSUE-1 ISSUE-2
```

### Add Comment

The `jira issue comment add` command adds comments to issues with support for markdown formatting.

```bash
# Add comment interactively
jira issue comment add

# Add comment directly
jira issue comment add ISSUE-1 "This is my comment"

# Add multi-line comment
jira issue comment add ISSUE-1 $'Line 1\n\nLine 2'

# Add internal/private comment (Service Desk)
jira issue comment add ISSUE-1 "Internal note" --internal

# Add comment from template file
jira issue comment add ISSUE-1 --template /path/to/comment.md

# Add comment from stdin
echo "Comment from stdin" | jira issue comment add ISSUE-1

# Add comment and open in browser
jira issue comment add ISSUE-1 "Done!" --web
```

### Add Worklog

The `jira issue worklog add` command logs time spent on issues.

```bash
# Add worklog interactively
jira issue worklog add

# Add worklog with time spent
jira issue worklog add ISSUE-1 "2d 1h 30m" --no-input

# Add worklog with comment
jira issue worklog add ISSUE-1 "4h" --comment "Implemented feature X" --no-input

# Add worklog with specific start date
jira issue worklog add ISSUE-1 "3h" --started "2024-01-15 09:00:00"

# Add worklog with timezone
jira issue worklog add ISSUE-1 "2h" --started "2024-01-15 14:00:00" --timezone "Europe/Berlin"

# Add worklog with Jira datetime format
jira issue worklog add ISSUE-1 "1h 30m" --started "2024-01-15T09:30:00.000+0200"

# Add worklog and update remaining estimate
jira issue worklog add ISSUE-1 "4h" --new-estimate "2h" --no-input
```

## Epic Management

### List Epics

The `jira epic list` command displays epics in an interactive explorer view with their associated issues.

```bash
# List all epics in explorer view
jira epic list

# List epics in table view
jira epic list --table

# List epics in plain text
jira epic list --table --plain

# List issues within a specific epic
jira epic list EPIC-1

# List epic issues in plain mode
jira epic list EPIC-1 --plain

# Filter epic issues
jira epic list EPIC-1 -ax -yHigh

# List epics by reporter
jira epic list -r$(jira me) -sOpen

# List epics with specific columns
jira epic list --table --plain --columns key,summary,status
```

### Create Epic

The `jira epic create` command creates new epics.

```bash
# Create epic interactively
jira epic create

# Create epic with parameters
jira epic create -n"Q1 Features" -s"All Q1 feature work" -yHigh -lq1 -b"Epic for Q1 2024 features"
```

### Add Issues to Epic

The `jira epic add` command adds existing issues to an epic.

```bash
# Add issues interactively
jira epic add

# Add multiple issues to epic
jira epic add EPIC-1 ISSUE-1 ISSUE-2 ISSUE-3
```

### Remove Issues from Epic

The `jira epic remove` command removes issues from their parent epic.

```bash
# Remove issues interactively
jira epic remove

# Remove specific issues from epic
jira epic remove ISSUE-1 ISSUE-2
```

