## Utility Commands

### Open in Browser

The `jira open` command opens the project or a specific issue in your web browser.

```bash
# Open project in browser
jira open

# Open specific issue in browser
jira open ISSUE-1
```

### Get Current User

The `jira me` command returns the current authenticated user's account ID or username.

```bash
# Get current user
jira me

# Use in scripts for self-assignment
jira issue assign ISSUE-1 $(jira me)
```

### Shell Completion

The `jira completion` command generates shell completion scripts.

```bash
# Generate bash completion
jira completion bash > /etc/bash_completion.d/jira

# Generate zsh completion
jira completion zsh > "${fpath[1]}/_jira"

# Generate fish completion
jira completion fish > ~/.config/fish/completions/jira.fish
```

## TUI Navigation

When using the interactive table or explorer views, the following keyboard shortcuts are available:

```
j/k or arrows    Navigate up/down
h/l or arrows    Navigate left/right
g/G              Jump to top/bottom
Ctrl+f           Page down
Ctrl+b           Page up
v                View issue details
m                Move/transition issue
Enter            Open in browser
c                Copy issue URL to clipboard
Ctrl+k           Copy issue key to clipboard
Ctrl+r or F5     Refresh list
w or Tab         Toggle sidebar focus (explorer view)
?                Show help
q/Esc/Ctrl+c     Quit
```

## Scripting Examples

### Tickets Created Per Day This Month

```bash
#!/usr/bin/env bash

tickets=$(jira issue list --created month --plain --columns created --no-headers | awk '{print $2}' | awk -F'-' '{print $3}' | sort -n | uniq -c)

echo "${tickets}" | while IFS=$'\t' read -r line; do
  day=$(echo "${line}" | awk '{print $2}')
  count=$(echo "${line}" | awk '{print $1}')
  printf "Day #%s: %s\n" "${day}" "${count}"
done
```

### Number of Tickets Per Sprint

```bash
#!/usr/bin/env bash

sprints=$(jira sprint list --table --plain --columns id,name --no-headers)

echo "${sprints}" | while IFS=$'\t' read -r id name; do
  count=$(jira sprint list "${id}" --plain --no-headers 2>/dev/null | wc -l)
  printf "%10s: %3d\n" "${name}" $((count))
done
```

### Bulk Update Issues

```bash
#!/usr/bin/env bash

# Get all open bugs assigned to me
issues=$(jira issue list -tBug -sOpen -a$(jira me) --plain --columns key --no-headers)

# Move each to "In Progress"
for issue in $issues; do
  jira issue move "$issue" "In Progress" --comment "Starting work"
done
```

## Summary

JiraCLI provides a comprehensive command-line interface for all common Jira operations, making it ideal for developers who prefer terminal-based workflows. The tool excels at issue management (list, create, edit, move, assign, comment), epic and sprint management, and provides powerful filtering with JQL support. Its interactive TUI with vim-like navigation offers a fast, keyboard-driven experience, while plain text and JSON output modes enable seamless integration with shell scripts and automation pipelines.

The tool's flexibility in configuration (supporting Cloud, Server, and Data Center installations with multiple auth methods) combined with its POSIX-compliant flags makes it highly adaptable to different environments and workflows. Whether you're quickly checking issue status, bulk-updating tickets, or building automated CI/CD integrations, JiraCLI provides the functionality needed to efficiently manage Jira without leaving your terminal.
